To find the inverse of a 2x2 matrix A = \begin{bmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{bmatrix}, we can use the formula:

A⁻¹ = \frac{1}{ad - bc} \begin{bmatrix} d & -b \\ -c & a \end{bmatrix}

In this case, A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 & 1 \\ 1 & 3 \end{bmatrix}, so a = 2, b = 1, c = 1, and d = 3.

First, we need to find the determinant, which is (ad - bc):

Determinant = (2 * 3) - (1 * 1) = 6 - 1 = 5

Now, we can find the inverse using the formula:

A⁻¹ = \frac{1}{5} \begin{bmatrix} 3 & -1 \\ -1 & 2 \end{bmatrix}

So, the inverse of matrix A is:

A⁻¹ = \begin{bmatrix} 3/5 & -1/5 \\ -1/5 & 2/5 \end{bmatrix}
